---
/**
 * Hub: crypto tax. Port of cryptoTaxView on the shared engine. Worked example by
 * investmentTax(). Federal only; state deferred with the rest of the block.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import CryptoTaxCalculator from '../../components/calculators/CryptoTaxCalculator.tsx';
import { investmentTax } from '../../lib/capital-gains';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

// $90k wages, $3k staking, $5k short-term and $15k long-term crypto gains, single.
const ex = investmentTax({
  status: 'single', otherOrdinaryIncome: 93000,
  shortTermGains: 5000, longTermGains: 15000, applyStandardDeduction: true,
});
---

<Base
  title="Crypto tax calculator 2026 — Bitcoin, staking, NFTs"
  description="Calculate 2026 federal tax on crypto: short vs long-term gains at 0/15/20%, staking as ordinary income, and why wash-sale rules don't apply."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Crypto tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The IRS treats crypto as property, not currency — so every sale is a taxable gain or loss.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Selling, swapping or spending crypto is a taxable event: you owe tax on the
    gain since you acquired it. Held a year or less, it is a short-term gain at
    ordinary rates; held longer, it is long-term at 0/15/20%. Staking rewards are
    ordinary income when you receive them. This works out the federal tax across
    all of it, and — unlike stocks — no wash-sale rule limits your losses.
  </p>

  <CryptoTaxCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(5000)} short-term, {formatMoney(15000)} long-term, {formatMoney(3000)} staking</h2>
  <p>
    A single filer with {formatMoney(90000)} of wages has {formatMoney(5000)} of
    short-term crypto gains, {formatMoney(15000)} of long-term gains, and
    {formatMoney(3000)} of staking rewards:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Tax</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Wages, staking and short-term gains at ordinary rates</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.ordinaryTaxTotal)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Long-term gains ({formatMoney(15000)}) at 0/15/20%</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.preferentialTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total federal tax</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalFederalTax)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The {formatMoney(15000)} long-term gain is taxed at 15% — {formatMoney(ex.preferentialTax)} —
    while the short-term gain and staking are folded into ordinary income at this
    filer's regular rate. Holding the coins that produced the short-term gain past
    a year would have moved them to the 15% rate too.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How is cryptocurrency taxed?</h3>
    <p>
      As property. When you dispose of it — sell for dollars, swap one coin for
      another, or pay for something — you realize a capital gain or loss equal to
      the change in value since you acquired it. Short-term (≤1 year) is taxed at
      ordinary rates, long-term (&gt;1 year) at 0/15/20%.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Are staking rewards taxed?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes — as ordinary income at their fair market value when you gain control of
      them, per IRS Revenue Ruling 2023-14, whether or not you sell. That value
      becomes your cost basis, so a later sale is a capital gain or loss from
      there. Mining as a business can instead be self-employment income.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Do wash-sale rules apply to crypto?</h3>
    <p>
      Not currently. The wash-sale rule that blocks a loss when you rebuy a
      security within 30 days applies to stocks, not to crypto, because crypto is
      property rather than a security. You can sell a coin at a loss, claim it, and
      buy it straight back — a live tax-loss-harvesting advantage, though proposed
      law could close it.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is swapping one coin for another taxable?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes. Trading Bitcoin for Ethereum is a sale of the Bitcoin at its dollar
      value that day, and a taxable gain or loss — there is no like-kind exchange
      for crypto. The same applies to spending crypto on goods.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What about NFTs?</h3>
    <p>
      NFTs are property too. A flip within a year is a short-term gain; held
      longer, long-term. Some NFTs may count as collectibles, which carry a top
      long-term rate of 28% rather than 20% — a nuance beyond this calculator, so
      check an NFT's classification if it is a large gain.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/">Capital gains tax calculator</a> — stocks use the same rates</li>
    <li><a href="/cost-basis-calculator/">Cost basis calculator</a> — track basis across coin lots</li>
    <li><a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">Quarterly tax calculator</a> — no one withholds on crypto gains</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Federal estimate for the 2026 tax year. State tax on crypto gains is extra and
    not modeled here. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
